        <div xml:id="KT62-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">talaimakaḷ iṭantalaippāṭṭiṉkaṇ kūṭaluṟu neñciṟkuc colliyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered to the heart that was full of the coitus during the meeting at the [same?] place by HIM.</p>
          </div>



        <div xml:id="KT62">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                kōṭa letirmukaip pacuvī mullai</l>
<l>                nāṟitaḻk kuvaḷaiyō ṭiṭaippaṭa viraii</l>
<l>                yaitutoṭai māṇṭa kōtai pōla</l>
<l>                naṟiya ṇallōṇ mēṉi</l>
<l>                muṟiyiṉum vāyvatu muyaṅkaṟku miṉitē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
             <l>The body of [my] good lady who is fragrant</l>
             <l rend="indent">like a garland glorious in a beautiful winding [of flowers]</l>
             <l rend="indent">– jasmine in fresh bloom [and] opening buds</l>
             <l rend="indent4">of the white Malabar lily</l>
             <l rend="indent">fragrantly interwoven with waterlilies of scented petals<note place="foot">The subtle syntax of the lines 1-4 is nearly unmarked and accordingly left to an effort of interpretation (see Wilden 1999: 219f.).</note>,</l>
             <l>it is excellent, even if it
                <choice>
                    <seg>will pass, and sweet to embrace.<note place="foot">The analysis (deviating from Cām.) of <term xml:lang="ta">muṟiyiṉum</term> as a concessive to <term xml:lang="ta">muṟi</term> goes back to Tieken 1997: 314f. (see also Wilden 1999: 217).</note></seg>
                    <seg>surpasses a shoot [in tenderness] and [is] sweet/sweeter to embrace.<note place="foot">Thus the usual interpretation, which follows Cām. In favour of it could be said that the comparison woman – sprout is one of the Caṅkam standard comparisons.</note></seg>
                </choice>
             </l>


             
                </lg>
        </div>
